<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-343-693  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 343 693.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>DBMS  March 1989 v2 n3 p42(9).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The art of distribution. (includes related articles on Codd andData Consulting Group VP Chris Date's rules describing distributeddatabases, office politics and communications links)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Dowgiallo, Ed.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>True distributed databases, databases that permit users andprograms to access data divided among physically separatecomputers without knowing or caring about the data's actuallocation, do not yet exist.andP;  Currently, vendors apply the termdistributed database applications to mean the application involvesa single logical database whose tables reside on differentcomputers.andP;  The two most basic database operations are joins, whenend data is combined by a single machine and presented to theuser, and updates, when a single transaction updates tables on twoor more machines.andP;  To date, most vendors have implemented onlyjoins.andP;  Database administrators must know how the systemcoordinates distributed operations.andP;  Distributed database is a newtechnology.andP;  It will be several years before a distributeddatabase meets the fundamental criterion of appearing the same asa database that is not distributed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Distributed Data BasesTrendsTechnology.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>